WEBVTT

00:02.895 --> 00:04.670
♪

00:06.565 --> 00:08.298
[sighs]

00:09.235 --> 00:11.593
♪<i> I want to break free</i> ♪

00:13.239 --> 00:16.098
♪<i> I want to break free</i> ♪

00:16.925 --> 00:18.183
♪<i> I want to</i> ♪

00:18.335 --> 00:20.185
♪<i> Break free from your lies</i> ♪

00:20.337 --> 00:22.746
♪<i> You're so self-satisfied</i> ♪

00:22.765 --> 00:25.357
♪<i> I don't need you</i> ♪

00:26.676 --> 00:29.153
♪<i> I've got to break free</i> ♪

00:31.198 --> 00:33.348
♪<i> God knows</i> ♪

00:34.426 --> 00:38.370
♪<i> God knows</i>
<i> I want to break free</i> ♪

00:39.689 --> 00:42.207
♪<i> I want to break free.</i> ♪

00:43.860 --> 00:44.951
[Smithers sighs]

00:45.104 --> 00:47.771
Ah, the joy
of a completed to-do list.

00:47.773 --> 00:50.549
Shall we celebrate
by cracking open an amontillado?

00:50.626 --> 00:52.867
Uh, sir, you had
that cask of amontillado

00:52.887 --> 00:54.536
walled off two days ago.

00:54.555 --> 00:56.555
-Along with the salesman.
-[knocking]

00:56.632 --> 00:58.282
[salesman]
Are you still considering

00:58.284 --> 00:59.892
the Cask of the Month Club?

00:59.968 --> 01:02.061
After three months,
it pays for itself.

01:02.063 --> 01:03.896
I'm thinking about it.

01:03.972 --> 01:06.123
Anyway, Smithers, a tasting.

01:06.141 --> 01:09.193
What about this 1945 Bordeaux?

01:10.646 --> 01:13.130
Yes, that could give
my palate a little party.

01:13.132 --> 01:14.722
Palate, have at it.

01:14.742 --> 01:16.224
Oh.

01:16.302 --> 01:18.969
How I miss extra-venous fluids.

01:18.971 --> 01:21.154
Mm, you're getting notes
of cigar smoke,

01:21.231 --> 01:23.231
saffron-- Ooh, sandalwood.

01:23.309 --> 01:24.500
Yes, yes, all of those.

01:25.828 --> 01:28.587
And cupcake frosting
from a child's birthday party

01:28.664 --> 01:30.923
with notes of petting zoo
on the finish.

01:31.074 --> 01:33.759
Oh, I'm getting a little tipsy.

01:33.761 --> 01:35.427
Make sure you take two aspirin

01:35.504 --> 01:39.223
and drink plenty of water
before I go to bed.

01:40.601 --> 01:42.250
[whimpering]

01:42.328 --> 01:44.161
What is it?
what do you hear, boy?

01:44.163 --> 01:45.679
Dress shoes on linoleum.

01:45.831 --> 01:47.331
It's Smithers.

01:47.349 --> 01:48.590
Whenever he comes down here,
he wants

01:48.667 --> 01:51.151
someone to stay late
and do extra work.

01:53.781 --> 01:55.364
[whimpering]

01:56.784 --> 01:58.617
Homer, it's one taquito.

01:58.694 --> 01:59.843
It's not worth it.

01:59.845 --> 02:01.620
No snack left behind.

02:01.697 --> 02:03.347
I'll tell your story.

02:03.349 --> 02:04.698
[microwave dings]

02:04.850 --> 02:06.274
Simpson, come with me.

02:06.293 --> 02:07.793
[groans]
Can I bring my taquito?

02:07.944 --> 02:09.211
No.

02:11.373 --> 02:13.298
Mr. Burns wants
to impress his wine club,

02:13.300 --> 02:15.025
so he paid a million dollars

02:15.043 --> 02:17.118
for a very special bottle
of Gevrey-Chambertin

02:17.138 --> 02:19.096
once owned by Napoleon.

02:20.215 --> 02:21.715
Whoa, just like the laundry pods

02:21.867 --> 02:24.059
they lock up
at the Kwik-E-Mart.

02:26.054 --> 02:27.312
Wow.

02:27.464 --> 02:29.539
Turns out Napoleon fought
the Battle of Austerlitz

02:29.541 --> 02:31.057
just because he'd heard
there was

02:31.134 --> 02:32.876
an extraordinary
bottle of red there.

02:32.895 --> 02:36.638
And you need my expert skills
to keep watch over it.

02:36.715 --> 02:39.658
No, I need you to ride in the
back with it as a human airbag.

02:39.851 --> 02:41.326
Ooh, human.

02:41.403 --> 02:42.552
[phone rings]

02:42.554 --> 02:45.480
Smithers, I coughed up
my Adam's apple.

02:45.499 --> 02:46.390
Not again.

02:46.408 --> 02:47.649
I'm on my way, sir.

02:47.668 --> 02:50.002
Simpson, I need you
to bring the Napoleon wine

02:50.078 --> 02:52.045
directly to Mr. Burns' mansion.

02:52.080 --> 02:53.914
This is the most important job

02:53.990 --> 02:55.916
you've ever done
in your entire life.

02:55.992 --> 02:58.084
I'm glad to have
earned your trust.

02:58.237 --> 03:00.662
If there were anyone else
on Earth I could ask, I would.

03:00.739 --> 03:01.905
Thank you.

03:01.924 --> 03:02.997
[Burns]
<i> Hurry, Smithers.</i>

03:03.017 --> 03:05.058
<i> Now ants are circling it.</i>

03:06.412 --> 03:08.929
Okay, just get the bottle
back to Mr. Burns.

03:09.081 --> 03:11.356
First, select
the least bumpy route.

03:12.193 --> 03:13.841
Aah!
Where'd it go?!

03:13.861 --> 03:17.254
And now it is my great honor

03:17.272 --> 03:19.031
to christen this ship--

03:19.033 --> 03:21.107
-[grunts]
-Well, I never.

03:21.184 --> 03:23.744
No, wait, this did happen
once before.

03:26.540 --> 03:28.765
[all] Mazel tov!

03:28.784 --> 03:30.209
[grunts] Ow!

03:38.777 --> 03:39.609
Uh...

03:39.628 --> 03:40.610
[sighs]

03:40.612 --> 03:42.095
Mwah.

03:42.965 --> 03:44.765
[grunts]

03:46.118 --> 03:48.143
[pellet guns firing]

03:51.548 --> 03:52.648
Mm...

03:54.626 --> 03:56.384
[grunting]

03:57.387 --> 04:00.555
Oh, man, I'm so far
from Mr. Burns' mansion.

04:00.632 --> 04:01.982
Where even am I?

04:02.058 --> 04:03.408
I'll give you a hint, dumbass.

04:03.560 --> 04:05.059
You live here.

04:05.137 --> 04:06.894
Give me another hint.

04:06.914 --> 04:09.139
Okay, Homer, you got
a million-dollar bottle of wine.

04:09.141 --> 04:11.141
For once in your life,
don't be stupid.

04:11.143 --> 04:13.252
Put it somewhere safe.

04:13.403 --> 04:15.145
Safe, safe.

04:15.163 --> 04:17.631
Wait, a safe.

04:20.319 --> 04:21.409
[grunts]

04:21.428 --> 04:25.079
Safe. So this is
what being smart feels like.

04:25.157 --> 04:27.340
[chuckles]
I'll reward myself

04:27.417 --> 04:29.993
with a quick garage nap
in the car.

04:29.995 --> 04:32.512
I'll just turn it on
to keep warm and--

04:32.589 --> 04:33.755
No.

04:33.832 --> 04:35.665
Staying smart.

04:35.667 --> 04:37.091
[snoring]

04:37.111 --> 04:38.777
Huh? Wha--
Oh, no!

04:38.779 --> 04:40.520
I need to get to Burns' mansion.

04:40.672 --> 04:41.838
You're exhausted.

04:41.840 --> 04:44.024
At least eat dinner
before you go.

04:44.100 --> 04:46.952
Mmm, this is the best stew ever.

04:47.103 --> 04:48.194
Oh, it's nothing special.

04:48.196 --> 04:49.937
Just beef, carrots, onions,

04:50.015 --> 04:51.364
garlic and bay leaves.

04:51.441 --> 04:52.774
Well, it's delicious.

04:52.851 --> 04:53.867
Oh, and some wine.

04:53.943 --> 04:56.444
What kind of wine?

04:56.522 --> 04:58.946
I didn't want to use
the good nine-dollar bottle,

04:58.966 --> 05:01.541
so I just used this old one.

05:01.693 --> 05:03.451
[screaming]

05:03.470 --> 05:04.303
How? No.

05:04.454 --> 05:06.638
No, I was smart.
I was smart.

05:06.790 --> 05:08.181
So smart.

05:09.977 --> 05:11.793
What?
I don't understand.

05:11.812 --> 05:13.437
It's still locked.

05:15.316 --> 05:17.207
-Huh?
-[Bart] Hey, Homer.

05:17.209 --> 05:19.209
What the hell
kind of safe is this?

05:19.211 --> 05:21.469
Remember?
You punched a hole in the wall

05:21.547 --> 05:24.472
when Major League Baseball
added the pitch clock.

05:24.550 --> 05:27.308
I like my sports slow,
and they knew that.

05:27.386 --> 05:28.976
Marge, you don't understand.

05:28.996 --> 05:30.737
That wine you used in the stew

05:30.814 --> 05:32.146
was Burns' wine.

05:32.166 --> 05:34.908
It cost a million dollars!

05:35.060 --> 05:36.501
Oh, no. No!

05:36.653 --> 05:38.078
No, no, no, no, no, no.

05:38.230 --> 05:40.188
A million dollars?

05:40.190 --> 05:41.731
A million dollars!

05:41.733 --> 05:42.824
I don't want stew.

05:42.843 --> 05:44.676
I want mac and cheese.

05:44.753 --> 05:47.429
-Eat your million-dollar stew.
-[grunts]

05:48.574 --> 05:49.473
[groans]

05:55.414 --> 05:57.247
You used all
of the million-dollar wine?

05:57.249 --> 05:59.432
It's what the recipe calls for.

05:59.434 --> 06:01.509
You should have written
your name on the bottle.

06:01.511 --> 06:04.387
Like I do with that special tea
that makes me regular.

06:04.423 --> 06:06.089
Regular?
You didn't go the whole time

06:06.091 --> 06:07.866
we were in
the Wisconsin Dells.

06:07.943 --> 06:09.868
That's why I got the tea!

06:09.870 --> 06:11.444
That I label.

06:11.446 --> 06:12.946
[Smithers]
Simpson.

06:13.098 --> 06:15.523
Why haven't you delivered the
bottle to Mr. Burns' mansion?

06:15.601 --> 06:16.950
Before I answer that,

06:16.952 --> 06:19.086
try some of this delicious stew.

06:20.196 --> 06:23.030
Mmm, the onions, the garlic,

06:23.108 --> 06:25.700
the red wine
from the 19th century.

06:25.719 --> 06:27.277
[groans]

06:27.279 --> 06:28.202
Aah!

06:28.280 --> 06:29.721
It's not what you think.

06:29.798 --> 06:33.283
Marge cooked the wine into stew.

06:33.285 --> 06:35.727
Stew that we ate.

06:35.804 --> 06:37.712
-[growls]
-Uh,

06:37.789 --> 06:38.897
if you need to
strangle the boy for a minute,

06:39.048 --> 06:40.232
that's what he's here for.

06:40.308 --> 06:42.308
Eh, it's what I bring
to the table.

06:42.310 --> 06:44.127
Oh, God, this is going
to take Mr. Burns

06:44.146 --> 06:46.238
to a horrifying level of fury.

06:46.389 --> 06:48.556
He built this lumber mill
just to kill us.

06:48.575 --> 06:50.558
Oh, that explains it.

06:50.636 --> 06:54.137
Waylon, Homer really did try
to keep it safe.

06:54.156 --> 06:56.230
This is all my fault.

06:56.232 --> 06:59.751
I can't believe I was undone
by Marge Simpson.

06:59.753 --> 07:02.069
[crying]

07:02.147 --> 07:03.913
Mm. Hmm?

07:04.983 --> 07:07.984
Okay, I know things
look kind of bad.

07:07.986 --> 07:10.820
But there is a way out of this.

07:10.822 --> 07:12.172
This isn't "kind of bad."

07:12.248 --> 07:13.748
This is a catastrophe.

07:13.825 --> 07:17.494
If I may-- for you,
catastrophe is a new thing.

07:17.496 --> 07:20.772
But for me, it's just
another day at the office.

07:20.849 --> 07:23.500
What the hell are talking about,
you incompetent nitwit?

07:23.502 --> 07:25.760
Oh, Smithers,
Smithers, Smithers.

07:25.837 --> 07:27.020
Let me explain.

07:27.096 --> 07:28.280
Maggie, my note.

07:29.357 --> 07:31.357
♪<i> In the course</i>
<i> of my long life</i> ♪

07:31.359 --> 07:33.601
-Aah!
-♪<i> I've learned a golden rule</i> ♪

07:33.603 --> 07:35.937
♪<i> To escape the blame</i>
<i> and avoid the shame</i> ♪

07:35.939 --> 07:37.956
♪<i> When I've been an utter fool</i> ♪

07:38.033 --> 07:40.867
♪<i> I simply cover it up</i> ♪

07:42.037 --> 07:44.296
-♪<i> Cover it up?</i> ♪
-♪<i> Cover it up?</i> ♪

07:44.298 --> 07:46.131
♪<i> Cover it up, cover it up</i> ♪

07:46.133 --> 07:48.391
♪<i> Lost her wedding ring</i>
<i> one winter</i> ♪

07:48.393 --> 07:50.451
♪<i> Cover it up, cover it up</i> ♪

07:50.529 --> 07:52.637
♪<i> Made one with a 3D printer</i> ♪

07:52.789 --> 07:54.622
♪<i> Cover it up, cover it up</i> ♪

07:54.624 --> 07:56.716
♪<i> I cut down Flanders'</i>
<i> cherry tree</i> ♪

07:56.793 --> 07:58.793
♪<i> And then did tell a lie</i> ♪

07:58.795 --> 08:00.645
♪<i> I blamed it on some teens</i> ♪

08:00.797 --> 08:03.148
♪<i> Who were wedgie-ing this guy</i> ♪

08:03.150 --> 08:05.058
♪<i> Neck high</i> ♪

08:05.060 --> 08:06.818
-♪<i> Cover it up</i> ♪
-♪<i> Cover it up</i> ♪

08:06.895 --> 08:10.989
♪<i> I can't recall the lyrics</i>
<i> to the verse I'm singing now</i> ♪

08:11.066 --> 08:13.325
♪<i> Who cares?</i>
<i> I'll make some new words up</i> ♪

08:13.401 --> 08:16.077
[scatting]

08:17.906 --> 08:19.981
♪<i> I love you, "Spingfield"</i> ♪

08:20.058 --> 08:21.391
♪<i> Trick the red light camera</i> ♪

08:21.393 --> 08:24.227
♪<i> When you're rushing</i>
<i> to get home</i> ♪

08:24.229 --> 08:26.229
♪<i> Forgot to bring a doggy bag</i> ♪

08:26.231 --> 08:28.507
♪<i> Just use a garden gnome</i> ♪

08:28.583 --> 08:30.008
♪<i> I caused so many meltdowns</i> ♪

08:30.010 --> 08:32.752
♪<i> So I use my little fix</i> ♪

08:32.754 --> 08:34.754
♪<i> We know you caused</i>
<i> those meltdowns</i> ♪

08:34.831 --> 08:37.015
♪<i> No, you only knew of six</i> ♪

08:37.017 --> 08:39.242
♪<i> Let's fix my wife's--</i>
<i> not my-- mistake</i> ♪

08:39.244 --> 08:41.335
-♪<i> Cover it up</i> ♪
-♪<i> And fill this fancy jug</i> ♪

08:41.413 --> 08:43.429
-♪<i> With fake</i> ♪
-♪<i> Cover it up</i> ♪

08:43.431 --> 08:46.525
-♪<i> Make a woo-hoo</i>
<i> out of a d'oh</i> ♪
-♪<i> Just cover it up</i> ♪

08:46.601 --> 08:48.768
♪<i> Cover it up</i>
<i> and they'll never</i> ♪

08:48.770 --> 08:52.030
♪<i> Even know</i> ♪

08:52.032 --> 08:54.074
♪<i> Cover it up!</i> ♪

08:55.852 --> 08:57.443
Mm, I can't resist

08:57.445 --> 08:59.596
a musical number
that advances the plot.

08:59.598 --> 09:02.098
-I'm in.
-But how do we cover this up?

09:02.100 --> 09:04.100
It's not gonna be easy.

09:04.102 --> 09:06.102
Mr. Burns is planning
to pour the Napoleon wine

09:06.104 --> 09:09.455
for some of the most discerning
wine connoisseurs in the world.

09:09.457 --> 09:12.125
You know, wine is
basically just chemistry.

09:12.201 --> 09:14.110
Maybe you need someone
who knows all about

09:14.112 --> 09:16.596
the chemistry of alcohol.

09:18.116 --> 09:20.633
Wine is the red one, right?

09:20.710 --> 09:22.302
Well, I understand your dilemma,

09:22.304 --> 09:24.454
but I am right
in the middle of an experiment

09:24.456 --> 09:28.215
to develop the proverbial
six-pack abdominals.

09:29.628 --> 09:33.129
-[both groan]
-I know, but it's
what the ladies want.

09:33.148 --> 09:35.407
I think they just want
someone who listens.

09:35.483 --> 09:37.967
Well, I don't have
a contraption for that.

09:37.969 --> 09:39.744
Professor, maybe if I

09:39.746 --> 09:42.488
-rephrase it like this.
-♪

09:42.490 --> 09:44.207
-♪<i> Cover it up!</i> ♪
-♪<i> Flavin!</i> ♪

09:47.070 --> 09:49.070
Uh, well, based on my analysis

09:49.072 --> 09:52.424
of the last drops
of the stewified Napoleon wine,

09:52.426 --> 09:55.910
I've created a replica
out of diammonium phosphate,

09:55.987 --> 09:58.763
calcium carbonate and 14 CCs

09:58.765 --> 10:01.600
of Manischewitz.

10:01.676 --> 10:02.934
[sniffs]

10:03.995 --> 10:06.346
Mmm.
That's, uh, that's amazing.

10:06.422 --> 10:08.998
-So we did it?
-We did it.

10:09.000 --> 10:11.092
Uh, I, uh, did it, yes.

10:11.094 --> 10:13.594
And now, just
to ensure I've removed

10:13.596 --> 10:16.597
the radioactive isotope
found in all wines

10:16.599 --> 10:19.492
made after the dawn
of the nuclear age...

10:21.029 --> 10:22.528
Perfect.

10:22.530 --> 10:24.497
[detector clicking]

10:26.201 --> 10:28.126
Uh, should I be worried
about that?

10:28.128 --> 10:30.186
Are you planning
on having children?

10:30.188 --> 10:32.038
I never planned
any of my children.

10:32.040 --> 10:34.341
Uh, well, it is what it is.

10:35.694 --> 10:38.044
I call to order this meeting
with our credo,

10:38.046 --> 10:39.620
"Never drink something younger

10:39.698 --> 10:42.140
or date something older
than you."

10:42.142 --> 10:43.958
[all]
To pointless excess.

10:43.960 --> 10:45.143
And now, the main event:

10:45.220 --> 10:48.146
a bottle of wine once held
by Napoleon himself.

10:48.148 --> 10:50.890
So, raise a glass
and bend an "Elba."

10:50.967 --> 10:52.800
[laughing]

10:52.802 --> 10:55.487
Smithers, release the cork.

10:57.491 --> 10:59.065
Moment of truth.

10:59.067 --> 11:00.992
You know, our marriage
really could use

11:00.994 --> 11:03.328
fewer moments of truth.

11:04.331 --> 11:07.832
Now that's million-buck chuck!

11:07.834 --> 11:10.727
Complex with a hint of

11:10.729 --> 11:12.462
doy-yoy-yoy-yoy-yoy-yoing!

11:13.990 --> 11:14.914
Mm.

11:14.991 --> 11:16.916
The cover-up worked!

11:17.068 --> 11:20.086
And tonight,
we'll have cover-up sex.

11:20.163 --> 11:22.572
Ooh, it'll be my first.

11:22.574 --> 11:24.349
[laughing] No, it won't.

11:25.927 --> 11:28.353
I can't believe
we pulled that off.

11:28.355 --> 11:31.022
I feel a little guilty
and a little scared.

11:31.024 --> 11:32.932
Like the first time
I fast-forwarded

11:33.084 --> 11:34.359
through a commercial.

11:34.361 --> 11:35.360
Don't feel bad.

11:35.437 --> 11:36.677
With the money
those billionaires

11:36.697 --> 11:37.862
spend on one bottle,

11:37.864 --> 11:39.346
it could buy every poor person
in the world

11:39.424 --> 11:42.016
an inexpensive
but very drinkable rosé.

11:42.093 --> 11:44.185
Those monsters.

11:44.262 --> 11:46.705
They are.
And I do their bidding.

11:46.781 --> 11:48.781
[crying]

11:48.858 --> 11:51.935
I'm just as bad, if not worse,
because I know better.

11:51.937 --> 11:53.878
I'm even starting
to look like Mr. Burns.

11:53.955 --> 11:55.772
Hump!

11:55.774 --> 11:59.792
Sometimes I feel like I've
only got this much soul left.

11:59.794 --> 12:01.127
Don't worry, Waylon.

12:01.129 --> 12:03.204
There's plenty of soul
where that came from.

12:03.206 --> 12:05.223
You know, we've still got

12:05.300 --> 12:07.951
a lot of this Frinky drinky.

12:07.953 --> 12:10.228
Think how many wrongs
we could right

12:10.305 --> 12:13.957
if we sold just one more
million-dollar bottle.

12:13.959 --> 12:16.142
Are you slurring
what I think you're slurring?

12:16.219 --> 12:18.737
Yes.
What if we sell fake wine

12:18.813 --> 12:20.964
to the rich to give to the poor?

12:20.966 --> 12:22.699
Like Robin Hood.

12:25.971 --> 12:27.203
♪

12:42.170 --> 12:43.595
[grunting, exclaiming]

12:47.583 --> 12:49.225
[grunts]

12:59.095 --> 13:01.112
I'm cleansing my soul.

13:01.189 --> 13:03.673
And I'm getting out
of the house.

13:03.675 --> 13:05.200
[gavel bangs]

13:06.102 --> 13:07.844
[quiet chatter]

13:07.846 --> 13:09.195
We're doing this.

13:09.197 --> 13:10.955
We're actually
going to Robin Hood

13:11.032 --> 13:12.290
a bottle of fake wine.

13:12.292 --> 13:15.460
Look at all these mega-rich
wine connoisseurs.

13:15.462 --> 13:18.871
I've never seen so many people
not wearing baseball caps.

13:18.948 --> 13:21.299
And that's Jim Sprawldon
from the Sprawl-Mart fortune.

13:21.301 --> 13:24.285
And from Sam's Club,
there's Marcus Club himself.

13:24.362 --> 13:26.529
Oh... I can ask him
to bring back

13:26.548 --> 13:29.532
Marcus's Choice
cinnamon apple dryer sheets.

13:29.534 --> 13:32.368
